Likewise, the Abrahamic religions share similar features distinguishing them from other categories of religions:
all of their theological traditions are, to some extent, influenced by the depiction of the God of Israel in the Hebrew Bible;
all of them trace their roots to Abraham as a common genealogical and spiritual patriarch.In the Abrahamic tradition, God is one, eternal, omnipotent, omniscient, and the creator of the universe.

The Tanakh and siddur describe Shabbat as having three purposes:
To commemorate God's creation of the universe, on the seventh day of which God rested from (or ceased) his work;
To commemorate the Israelites' Exodus and redemption from slavery in ancient Egypt;
As a "taste" of Olam Haba (the Messianic Age).Judaism accords Shabbat the status of a joyous holy day.

